Individual No 1; 
singing from the top of a 15m conifer
based on a forum question by Sean Roach, I originally used auduboni (see e.g., Campbell et al Birds BC); IOC includes munroi, which Campbell et al do not recognize, so for XC purposes munroi may be better, but see Phillips 1991, which puts a "?" for inclusion in the Canadian Rockies.  To me, birds here look most like auduboni types.

Individual No 3; 
singing from exposed perch on the top of a 15m spruce; 
interval shortened by 20 seconds at 1:53
based on a forum question by Sean Roach, I originally used auduboni (see e.g., Campbell et al Birds BC); IOC includes munroi, which Campbell et al do not recognize, so for XC purposes munroi may be better, but see Phillips 1991, which puts a "?" for inclusion in the Canadian Rockies in the range of munroi.  To me, birds here look most like auduboni types.
